            <lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">Geology Lecture 4 1805</hi>
            <lb/>
            <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag1"
                ref="#misc_681"
                type="miscellaneous">
               <term xml:id="tag1">
          It has often happened during the
        </term>
            </rs>
            <lb/>
progress of science that two doctrines<lb/>
immediately opposite have been supposed<lb/>
with great powers of reasoning and almost<lb/>
with equal plausibility<lb/>
Such a circumstance however almost<lb/>
always marks the infancy of the<lb/>
study and the imperfection of the<lb/>
methods of investigation .<lb/>
It proves that speculation has been<lb/>
merely employed <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">or</del> or partial<lb/>
facts only examined.<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="4"
                xml:id="pb-4"
                facs="#i4"/>
            <lb/>
And the Philosophical enquirer in<lb/>
opposing supposition to supposition<lb/>
and error to error will instantly percieve<lb/>
the insufficiency of either class of<lb/>
opinions: and will thus preserve<lb/>
the mind free from doubt from the<lb/>
prejudice of false systems from mistakes<lb/>
and confusion.-<lb/>
This method may be sometimes<lb/>
applied with <add xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0">great</add> success in the examination<lb/>
of Geological Theories.<lb/>
It removes the necessity of strict<lb/>
discussion and it often devellopes<lb/>
absurdity without the assistance<lb/>
of<del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough"> labour</del> laborious logical deductions<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="5"
                xml:id="pb-5"
                facs="#i5"/>
            <lb/>
            <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag2"
                ref="#person_266"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag2" type="person">
          Buffon
        </name>
            </rs> in his theory of the Globe<lb/>
supports that the surface is constantly<lb/>
becoming colder<lb/>
            <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag3"
                ref="#person_866"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag3" type="person">
          M de Maillet
        </name>
            </rs> on the other hand conceives<lb/>
that it is daily growing warmer<lb/>
The first attempts to prove that ice<lb/>
in the course of ages will extend even<lb/>
to the countries under the trop<del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">p</del>ics<lb/>
Whilst the last conceives that in no<lb/>
very distant period it will disappear<lb/>
even from the poles<lb/>
The one Author fears unless the energies<lb/>
of the Sun are capable of opposing<lb/>
the laws of nature our cultivated<lb/>
lands will become snow clad plains<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="6"
                xml:id="pb-6"
                facs="#i6"/>
            <lb/>
And the other dreads their conversion into<lb/>
burning deserts of sand, incapable of <lb/>
supporting vegetable life -<lb/>
It is scarcely possible to imagine two<lb/>
hypotheses in more perfect opposition; both<lb/>
have been defended with ingenuity both<lb/>
are founded upon mistakes -<lb/>
The one may be ballanced against the<lb/>
other there will be scarcely a perceptible<lb/>
difference in their weight and importance<lb/>
and they may be safely be given up together.<lb/>
The <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">work</hi> of <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag4"
                ref="#person_866"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag4" type="person">
          M. de Maillet
        </name>
            </rs> on Geology<lb/>
is called <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag5"
                ref="#otherwork_321"
                type="otherwork">
               <bibl xml:id="tag5">
                  <hi rend="underline">Telliamed</hi>
               </bibl>
            </rs> which is an anagram<lb/>
of his name a translation of it appeared<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="7"
                xml:id="pb-7"
                facs="#i7"/>
            <lb/>
in English in 1750 -<lb/>
The Author professes to devellope the<lb/>
opinions of an indian philosopher whom<lb/>
he had met at <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag6"
                ref="#place_1094"
                type="place">
               <name xml:id="tag6" type="place">
          Cairo
        </name>
            </rs> when the Consul<lb/>
General of France was in that City.<lb/>
Though he intended to produce a<lb/>
philosophical Theory He has given it<lb/>
in the form of a <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">Romance</hi> for the<lb/>
fables are more numerous than the facts<lb/>
and it affords much entertainment<lb/>
but little or no instruction.<lb/>
            <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag7"
                ref="#person_866"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag7" type="person">
          M. de Maillet
        </name>
            </rs> from having observed an<lb/>
increase of Land on several parts of<lb/>
the coast of the <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag8"
                ref="#place_1191"
                type="place">
               <name xml:id="tag8" type="place">
          mediterranean
        </name>
            </rs> conceives<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="8"
                xml:id="pb-8"
                facs="#i8"/>
            <lb/>
that there must be an uniform law of<lb/>
diminution of the Sea in consequence<lb/>
of which the whole surface must at<lb/>
length become dry land.<lb/>
His opinion is very similar to that<lb/>
ancient one of <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag9"
                ref="#person_906"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag9" type="person">
                  <hi rend="underline">Leucippus</hi>.
        </name>
            </rs>
            <lb/>
And he farther supposes that the whole<lb/>
of the Globe in Early ages was covered<lb/>
with water: and that from the slow<lb/>
and gradual disappearance of the <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">Ocean</hi>
            <lb/>
our present islands and continents<lb/>
have been formed and the existing<lb/>
order of things produced -<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="9"
                xml:id="pb-9"
                facs="#i9"/>
            <lb/>
I have mentioned this hypothesis because<lb/>
it is the foundation of the idea of the<lb/>
gradually increasing temperature of the<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">Land</hi>. For <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag10"
                ref="#person_866"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag10" type="person">
          M. de Maillet
        </name>
            </rs> justly conceives<lb/>
that if water disappears Fire must accumulate<lb/>
and that the <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">dry surface</hi> must soon become<lb/>
inhabitable.<lb/>
All his observation of facts however are<lb/>
partial and his notion of the dissipation<lb/>
of the moisture of our globe into space<lb/>
shows a total ignorance of the laws of<lb/>
            <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">evaporation</hi> which long before the<lb/>
time of the publication of his work<lb/>
had been fully <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">develop</del> develloped<lb/>
by <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag11"
                ref="#person_505"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag11" type="person">
          D<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> Hally.-
        </name>
            </rs>
            <lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="10"
                xml:id="pb-10"
                facs="#i10"/>
            <lb/>
This excellent Philosopher has proved from<lb/>
the most accurate data that the fluid<lb/>
raised from the ocean and the surface of<lb/>
the Earth in consequence of the solar<lb/>
heat is condensed by cold in the upper<lb/>
regions of the air and that from its<lb/>
deposition clouds are produced and dew<lb/>
and rain which water the Earth and<lb/>
support vegetable <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">life</del> and animal life<lb/>
and form rivers that return the<lb/>
superfluous moisture into the sea<lb/>
its <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">parent source</hi>.<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="11"
                xml:id="pb-11"
                facs="#i11"/>
            <lb/>
According to this beautiful system the foundations<lb/>
of which <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">are distinct truths</hi> there is a<lb/>
constant circulation of moisture upon our Globe.<lb/>
No portion rises above the atmosphere<lb/>
no portion is lost: and amidst a variety of<lb/>
combinations and <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">decompositions</hi>, the equilibrium<lb/>
is preserved  the quantity is unimpaired: and<lb/>
there is a constant application of it to the<lb/>
uses of <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">living beings</hi>.-<lb/>
Most of the important errors of the early<lb/>
Geological systems of the moderns may indeed<lb/>
be referred to a want of acquaintance in<lb/>
their Authors with the great facts blonging<lb/>
to the order of Nature: and to an<lb/>
ignorance of the real essence of the<lb/>
            <del xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                 rend="strikethrough">subterraneans</del> subterranean <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">Kingdom</hi>.<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="12"
                xml:id="pb-12"
                facs="#i12"/>
            <lb/>
|_<hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">Chemistry</hi> and <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">minerology</hi> till the<lb/>
middle of the last century were merely<lb/>
in the embryon state without order or<lb/>
beauty:<lb/>
And they offer the only true and permanent<lb/>
foundations on which a given Theory<lb/>
of the Earth can be erected.<lb/>
Not even the genius of a becker or a<lb/>
            <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
