He supposes a new class of Rocks which He<lb/>
calls the transitional Rocks to have been formed.<lb/>
            <lb/>
            <pb xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                n="48"
                xml:id="pb-48"
                facs="#i48"/>
            <lb/>
At the period of the deposition of the<lb/>
transitional Rocks <rs xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                xml:id="ttag79"
                ref="#person_267"
                type="person">
               <name xml:id="tag79" type="person">
          Werner
        </name>
            </rs> supposes the<lb/>
Ocean to have been peopled with living<lb/>
beings and hence He accounts for the shells<lb/>
and remains of Marine Animals existing<lb/>
in them.<lb/>
The last epoch in his Geology is the<lb/>
production of the secondary or highly stratified<lb/>
Masses containing <hi xmlns:conf="https://www.lancaster.ac.uk/library/ns/digital-library/config/1.0"
                rend="underline">in almost all their parts</hi>
